's just gravey to the whole situation.  I did post this in it's own thread.  But I thought I would add it here and let the mods delete the old one.<br>
<br>
I’m actually writing this in Word so I can do a spell and grammar check. Some of my spelling and grammar will still be wrong, but at least this way it will be a heck of a lot easier to read.<br>
<br>
Now the way that I look at Dark Age for magic and melee strength is how Mythic have said, or I think they said. Albion is evenly split for power of melee and magic. Hibernia is stronger in the magic but weaker in melee. And Midgard is stronger in melee and weaker in magic. Okay. We all know this, but lets but some basic numbers so it’s more of a visual thing, the higher the number the stronger ability is. Albion: melee=2, magic=2. Hibernia: melee=1, magic=3. Midgard: melee=3, magic=1.<br>
<br>
Okay. A simple basic concept for the above. The actual numbers I do not know. Heck, with all the changes being implemented over the release time, I bet Mythic doesn’t know off hand and would have to do some sort of an analyze on the programming. Now the game is released and it’s discovered that some of the programming does not work as they had intended and/or a spec line/class is unfinished. So they start adding things and fixing genuine, non-whiner problems. This changes the balance, which was originally envisioned slightly. Over all this is not a major problem. Until people start doing the degrade analysis of battles and comparing them to past ones and to other classes. See a problem? I do. People are comparing same category of class from other realms to their character. Woops. That doesn’t work, because each realm is a different balance of melee/magic from the other 2. It sounds simple but I get the feeling sometimes that a lot of people forget this.<br>
<br>
To balance fairly they should look at the class first to see if everything is working as was intended. Then to see how it compares with the idea of the power lvl for that realm. For example. If a main tank for Midgard is always having major trouble in soloing any green con mob then it needs to be looked at. And what I mean by trouble is almost being killed and you started at full health. Now it’s possible to lose any match because it’s a game based off of random numbers it’s possible to have a really bad string of bad numbers that can cause the death of a character. I myself was fighting a middle range con blue mob and was killed because the numbers went against me in that extremely rare case. Another reason for balancing would be to make a class or spec line a viable option to use. That kind of balancing, no one should have a problem with that.<br>
<br>
It’s when the whiners come in and say, nerf this! And nerf that! Why? Because I don’t have it or I don’t have a defence against it that makes that ability (or what ever they are crying about) useless or so weak that there would be no reason to use that ability. It’s this kind of “balancing” that bothers me to no end. Because if it’s done it’s not balancing to the original vision to what was intended. I think some of the whiners would want “their class” to be melee=3 and magic=3, while everyone who is against them should be a melee=1 and magic=1. Some of the other whiners I believe are looking for that perfectly “balanced” game. And if a perfectly balanced game came out there would still be this to consider, as Majin said, “there is always the Player Skill itself which you can’t balance.” For myself, every same con player that I have faced, which admittedly is not a lot, I have won, except for one battle. No excuses, I got outplayed by that player. It was fast and painless. If someone is playing a class that most people say is nerfed and can no longer be played then why do some still play? I’m going to use the scout as an example. Now if, according to the whiners that the scout has been nerfed and really is not a viable class any more. Then why is the top RP holder of my server a scout with 2,021,336 Realm points? Approximately 550,000 points ahead of the person in second? It’s because that person learned how to use what skills they have and the rest is player skill. From what I understand in EQ it’s all about what items you have. If you have the items, then you can go somewhere. If you do not have the items. Well. Sorry. I have found in DAoC that you can have inferior weapons to your target and still come out on top, because in this game player skill is more of a factor then what people realise. Don’t get me wrong. Items are still very important, but they are not the end all and be all that will either make or break a character.<br>
<br>
Wow! This is a heck of a lot longer then I had intended. To sum it up. Yes, some balancing is necessary for a game to work, but not the kind of balancing that most of the post at the Vault seems to address. After all, the majority of the “balancing” requests seem to come from whiners who, IMHO, don’t understand the appropriate level of balancing necessary for a game like this.<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#3B3B3B><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub175.ezboard.com/umelanu.showPublicProfile?language=EN>melanu</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(7/3/02 10:44:57 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub35.ezboard.com/fthesafehousefrm19.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3677.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: .</span><hr size=1> 1.  I don't think realm points are a good measure of balance in fact I said that above.<br>
<br>
2.  I do think realm points are a measure of time played or in this case the number of characters playing (thus more collective time)<br>
<br>
3.  I notice a big difference in the servers and I attribute that to population differences.  It was pointed out that a smaller more organized realm can win against a larger unorganized realm.  On Galahad the albs are extremely well organized and often out number us 2 to 1 or 3 to 1 or even 5 to 1.  So thus my post.  <br>
<br>
4.  I did NOT say people would HAVE to play a certain realm.  I never suggested it.  What I suggested is that people get a bonus for playing a realm that is lower in population.  An incentive to do something by no means forces people to do it.<br>
<br>
5.  The lurikeen uprising was so far a one time thing.  No question it did help that realm, but in the end it's not happening on every server.  Thus I see no great force towards balancing the servers.  If it happens on 5 servers I would change my mind, but I doubt it will.<br>
<br>
I am not suggesting nerfing anyone.  I am not suggesting that it be harder to level for realms with lots of active players over 40.  I am just suggesting that it would be nice to see an incentive program that rewarded people for playing underpopulated realms.  <br>
<br>
This would help in 2 ways.  The underpopulated realm would level faster and thus have more people 40+ (but thus also the bonus would go down)  and people would probably want to play on that server because it's easier to level.  Once they got 40+ then the bonus would go down as well.<br>
<br>
What I don't see is how anyone loses out on this?  Except for realms that are overpopulated and enjoy dominating their server.<br>
<br>
Mel<br>
